{{Infobox language |name=Pawnee |region=North-central [[Oklahoma]] |ethnicity=2,500 [[Pawnee people|Pawnee]] (2007)<ref name=e18/> |speakers=10 |date=2007 |ref=e18 |familycolor=American|states=[[United States]] |fam1=[[Caddoan languages|Caddoan]] |fam2=Northern |fam3=Pawnee–Kitsai |fam4=Pawnee languages |iso3=paw |glotto=pawn1254 |glottorefname=Pawnee |lingua=64-BAB-b |map=Pawnee lang.png |mapcaption=Pre-contact distribution of Pawnee |notice=IPA }}
The '''Pawnee language''' is a [[Caddoan languages|Caddoan language]] spoken by some [[Pawnee people|Pawnee]] Native Americans who now live in north-central [[Oklahoma]]. Their traditional historic lands were along the [[Platte River]] in what is now [[Nebraska]].
==Dialects== Two important [[dialect]] divisions are evident in Pawnee: South Band and ''Skiri''. The distinction between the two dialects rests on differences in their respective [[phonetics|phonetic]] inventory and [[lexicon]].
==Status== Once the language of thousands of Pawnees, today Pawnee is spoken by a shrinking number of elderly speakers. As more young people learn [[English language|English]] as their first language, the status of Pawnee declines towards [[extinct language|extinction]]. However, as of 2007, the Pawnee Nation is developing teaching materials for the local high school and for adult language classes. Now, there are extensive documentary materials in the language archived at the American Indian Studies Research Institute. <ref>http://www.ethnologue.com/language/paw</ref>
==Phonology== The following describes the South Band dialect.
===Consonants=== Pawnee has eight [[consonant]] [[phoneme]]s, and according to one analysis of medial- and final-position glottal stops, one may posit a ninth consonant phoneme.
{| class="wikitable" |- ! &nbsp; ! Bilabial ! Alveolar ! Velar ! Glottal |- ! '''Stop''' | align="center" | {{IPA|p}} | align="center" | {{IPA|t}} | align="center" | {{IPA|k}} | align="center" | {{IPA|(ʔ)}} |- ! '''Affricate''' | &nbsp; | align="center" | {{IPA|ts}} | &nbsp; | &nbsp; |- ! '''Rhotic''' | &nbsp; | align="center" | {{IPA|r}} | &nbsp; | &nbsp; |- ! '''Fricative''' | &nbsp; | align="center" | {{IPA|s}} | &nbsp; | align="center" | {{IPA|h}} |- ! '''Approximant''' | &nbsp; | &nbsp; | align="center" | {{IPA|w}} | &nbsp; |}
* {{IPA|/ʔ/}} is predictable when it occurs in the middle of words. However, since {{IPA|/ʔ/}} is not completely predictable at the end of words, it may also need to be considered as a (phonemic) consonant.
===Vowels===
Pawnee has four [[vowel length|short]] [[vowel]] phonemes and four [[vowel length|long]] counterparts (also phonemic).
{| class="wikitable" |- ! &nbsp; ! align="center" | Front ! align="center" | Back |- ! &nbsp;'''High'''&nbsp; | align="center" | {{IPA|i/iː}} | align="center" | {{IPA|u/uː}} |- ! &nbsp;'''Mid-low'''&nbsp; | align="center" | {{IPA|e/eː}} | align="center" | {{IPA|a/aː}} |}
==Morphology== Pawnee is an [[ergative-absolutive language|ergative-absolutive]] [[polysynthetic language]].
==Alphabet== The Pawnee [[alphabet]]{{citation needed|reason="alphabet" here looks dubious, since an alphabet doesn't have vowels, and if what is meant is vowel letters ... well, "e" and "ee" are not distinct vowel letters.|date=September 2017}} has 9 consonants and 8 vowels. The letters are relatively similar in pronunciation to their English counterparts.
===Consonants===
