{{Infobox language family |name=Tsouic |altname= |region=Central [[Taiwan]] |familycolor=Austronesian |child1=[[Tsou language|Tsou]] |child2=Southern Tsouic |glotto=none |glotto2=tsou1248 |glottoname2=Tsou |glotto3=kana1292 |glottoname3=Kanakanavu–Saaroa |map=Formosan languages.png |mapcaption=(yellow) Greater Tsouic }}
The '''Tsouic languages''' (also known as the '''Central Formosan languages''') are three [[Formosan languages]], [[Tsou language|Tsou]] proper and the Southern languages [[Kanakanabu language|Kanakanabu]] and [[Saaroa language|Saaroa]]. The Southern Tsouic languages of Kanakanabu and Saaroa have the smallest phonemic inventories out of all the Formosan languages, with each language having only 13 consonants and 4 vowels (Blust 2009:165).<ref name="Blust">Blust, Robert A. ''The Austronesian Languages''. Canberra: Pacific Linguistics, Research School of Pacific and Asian Studies, Australian National University, 2009. {{ISBN|0-85883-602-5}}, {{ISBN|978-0-85883-602-0}}.</ref> These two languages are highly endangered, as many Southern Tsouic speakers are shifting to [[Bunun language|Bunun]] and [[Mandarin Chinese]].
The Proto-Tsouic language was reconstructed by Japanese linguist Shigeru Tsichida in 1976, and is supported by Blust (1999) and Li (2008). However, Chang (2006)<ref name="Chang2006">Chang, Henry Yungli. 2006. "Rethinking the Tsouic Subgroup Hypothesis: A Morphosyntactic Perspective." In Chang, H., Huang, L. M., Ho, D. (eds.). ''Streams converging into an ocean: Festschrift in honor of Professor Paul Jen-Kuei Li on his 70th birthday.'' Taipei: Institute of Linguistics, Academia Sinica.</ref> and Ross (2009)<ref name="Ross2009">Ross, Malcolm. 2009. "Proto Austronesian verbal morphology: A reappraisal." In Alexander Adelaar and Andrew Pawley (eds.). ''Austronesian historical linguistics and culture history: a festschrift for Robert Blust''. Canberra: Pacific Linguistics.</ref> deny that Tsouic is a valid group; Ross places Southern Tsouic within ''Nuclear Austronesian'' (the family of the various proto-Austronesian reconstructions), but the [[Tsou language]] as a more divergent branch.
==Classification== *''[[Tsou language|Tsou]]'' *Southern Tsouic **''[[Kanakanabu language|Kanakanabu]]'' **''[[Saaroa language|Saaroa]]''
==Sound changes== The following sound changes from [[Proto-Austronesian language|Proto-Austronesian]] occurred in the Tsouic languages (Li 2008:215).<ref name="Li">Li, Paul Jen-kuei. 2008. "Time perspective of Formosan Aborigines." In Sanchez-Mazas, Alicia ed. ''Past human migrations in East Asia: matching archaeology, linguistics and genetics''. Taylor & Francis US.</ref> * *C, *d > c * *y > Proto-Tsouic *z * *R > r
